Unfortunately, that is not the tone of many meetings today and has long forgotten the promise of a ‘kinder, softer’ policy, if it had ever begun.
It is becoming increasingly clear that a dissenting opinion is not tolerated in the Labour Party and any opinion is judged on whether it is acceptable to the party leadership or not.
This began shortly after Jeremy became leader, colleagues who, as far as I knew, had a similar political outlook as I did, suddenly expected me to make a turnaround and take a position that I would otherwise never have agreed to, from subjects such as national security to the European single market.
Every time I speak in front of an audience, whatever I say, there are scandals on social media calling for my candidacy to be rejected as a Member of Parliament for the next elections, exposing the centre's politics and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments to my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who are dealing with a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but are not intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that serious scandals seem to be considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with every ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules, the party becomes more petty-minded.
For the past two years, I have often been advised to keep me busy, not just to proclaim my opinion loudly and then I would ‘not get in trouble’.
But I did not go into politics for that.
Since I became a member of Labour 32 years ago as a school child, provoked by the neglect of Thatcher's government which literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a city councillor and in my role as minister.
I have never kept my politics hidden, even in the last elections.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy stance and my doubts about the current leadership.
To those who have been propagating the motion Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country drags on to a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually I have only one message, and it is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my voters, whether they are members of Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not prevent me from acting according to what I think is in your interest.
Chris Leslie is Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
