North Korea says it will ‘never’ disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are causing more and more distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances, the country would not be able to unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important goodwill measures” in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing location, and vowing not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will in no case unilaterally disarm.”
Although Ri reiterated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it moves forward, it was noted that he did not reject unilateral denuclearization a priori, as Pyongyang used to do.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the very first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. urges ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only strengthen our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the US leader did last week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party were in this issue of denuclearization of South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such an impasse.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different than last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be targeted on the U.S. mainland so that after ‘Mr. Evil President’ Trump called Kim a ‘missile’ on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, promised Kim this year to the United Nations to take his courage to take steps to disarm, but said that much still needs to be done and that the sanctions should remain until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, that doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, however, told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must be continued vigorously and firmly until we have achieved the full, final, verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has implemented unanimous sanctions against North Korea to greatly reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would go back to Pyongyang next month to make preparations for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Almost a few hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea appealed to him about setting “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea promised this month during a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States were to take ‘consistent measures’.
He said Kim had told him that the “consistent measures” he wanted were security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students follow course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study throughout the night and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor noted that the students of the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basics of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course, which is unique in the US as far as he knows.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
In the course, which is organized for the first time this year, students will be taught the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had a severe sleep deficit during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, students see an image of a dorm room, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine when sleeping.
In another part, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of a heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we find that they have the right to know all of this, just as people have the right to know what consequences the choice of cigarettes has on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride on a night of study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, must be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who is studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, because he had taken lessons with the professor last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to stand up. They also need to be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, which can make you struggle to fall asleep.
