And now a page from the almanac of our ‘Sunday Morning’: 30 September 1882, today exactly 136 years ago, for whom well can count... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm ‘Hans’ Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the geiger counter.
The geiger counter has since become an icon in pop culture, for example in ‘Bells or Coronado’, a 1950 film with unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: ‘What the hell is that?’
Rogers: ‘That is a geiger counter, which is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you set up these headphones, you hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: “It’s really banging now!”
‘Hans’ Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains relevant.
