Germany's new warship delayed again
The latest frigate of the German Navy should have come into service in 2014, replacing the outdated warships of the Cold War era, but it will take at least one year before it is ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rhineland-Pfalz', the leading ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been part of the Navy in 2014, but the distressing problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 serve to replace the aged frigates of the Bremen class.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and a form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic characteristics.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates up to two years in a row, far away from home ports.
However, the constant delays mean that the advanced warships, which are designed to allow Germany to project its power overseas, are already obsolete by the time they are put into operation, Die Zeit notes.
The fatal frigate F125 has already made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and sent it back to the shipyard Blohm & Voss in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited some crucial 'software and hardware defects' that would render the warship useless if it were deployed in a combat mission.
Software defects were especially important because the vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class are served by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower on the frigates of the older Bremen class.
It also became clear that the ship is suffering from a serious overweight, which will reduce its performance and limit the Navy's capabilities to carry out further upgrades.
The Rhineland-Palatinate weighs 7,000 tons, twice as many as ships of a similar class deployed by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including the training of the crew, is already a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion, compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems that the newest frigates have in their grip become extra important because of the recent warnings that the power of the German Navy is diminishing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the parliamentary defence committee in Germany, acknowledged that the Navy actually "has a shortage of deployable ships".
The official said the problem has grown over time as a snowball, as old ships were taken out of service but no replacement vessels were delivered.
He complained that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class were available to be included in the Navy.
National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
New research conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bats, the brown big oar bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed in key locations around the estate to track the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cries of the bat and what kind of what does.
Next, a map of the habitat and a report are produced to create a detailed image on the landscape scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation advisor, hopes that the results show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making meadows and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, such as flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
Due to their night hunting habits, however, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who conduct regular examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue actions.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland’s ten species of bats live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
“Here in Threave we have a great environment for bats,” he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much is not yet known about bats and that is why the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the potentially unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their boys, potentially eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, or disturb them, or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, “We still need to learn a lot about our bats and of many of our species we simply don’t know how their populations are going.”
