Red glow update: Concentrations decrease in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decline in concentrations of Red glow in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the US).
According to the committee, reports are on fragmentary increases in the Red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are spots about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less places than last week.
Red glow has also been seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported off the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are ongoing reports of airway irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no reports of airway irritation were reported in the past week.
